Task 1 — Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic

Tool Used - 
I chose Canva (canva.com) for this task because it is free, works directly in the browser, and gives much better design 
results compared to what I could create in PowerPoint. It also doesn’t require any installation, which made it even more 
convenient to use.

What the Infographic Covers

I have divided the Visual Infographic Image into 3 segments:

1. What Digital Literacy Actually Is — I broke it into following pillars: finding information, communicating online, 
creating content, staying safe. 
I wanted to avoid just copy-pasting a textbook definition and explain each one simply instead.

2. Useful Tools for Students — Tools grouped by category: professional profiles (GitHub - Projects, LinkedIn - Networking, 
Kaggle - Data Science), coding practice (HackerRank, CodeChef), collaboration (Google Drive, Google Forms), and 
(NPTEL, Coursera) for skill development and learning. Things we'll actually use in college.

3. Safe Internet Habits — Password safety, two-factor authentication, phishing awareness, creating strong passwords
and UPI scam basics.

I kept it practical rather than overly technical. This task helped me understand digital literacy practically and improve 
my ability to present information clearly. It also increased my awareness of useful tools and online safety.
